&nbsp;
The symbol, at Columbia>, on the Upper West Side of New York, began on 17 April, not one day by chance: it was the one where the university president, Minouche Shafik, had gone to testify at the Congress about anti-Semitic events on campus. Shafik asked the NYPD to dismantle the camp created in the outside area of the school, a move that raised tensions and hardened the protest.&nbsp; From April 24, student occupations began in Ohio State, Stanford (Connecticut), Emory (Georgia), Arizona State, Austin (Texas), University of Pennsylvania, Chapel Hill (North Carolina), Ucla (California) and University of Delaware.
&nbsp;
At the same time the presence of police has increased > to preside over university campuses: in February, on 205 student demonstrations on campus, the police were present in twenty-seven, especially along the east coast. According to the last data, updated on Sunday, the agents preside over 150 out of 539 between universities and colleges recording occupations or, according to school boards, could be involved in protest events. According to Cnn, more than 1,500 people have been arrested in the last two weeks, but the figure is unclear. The Washington Post, referring to the same period, talks about 1200 people.
&nbsp;
The largest number of arrests took place on 30 April, with more than 400 protesters stopped by the police. Of these, about three hundred only at Columbia and City College in New York. Almost one hundred were arrested on 24 April at the University of Southern California. The handcuffs have taken so far on at least 30 campuses, in 23 states>. The others recorded demonstrations but without police intervention. The universities where at least 45 arrests were made are Columbia, Yale, Nyu, Northeastern University, Indiana University, Washington University, Virginia Tech, University of Southern California, Arizona State, University of Texas in Austin.&nbsp;

